questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Logic gates:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;electric circuit&lt;/span&gt;, which works on&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;simple Boolean algebra&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to perform a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;logical operation&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;one or more binary inputs&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that produce a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;single binary output&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Types&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of Logic gates:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;AND Gate&lt;/span&gt;: If both the inputs are high, it produces a high output.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Boolean algebra for AND gate is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;X = A. B&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_13.6.20_Pallavi_D21.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 403px; height: 184px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And &lt;strong&gt;NAND gate is opposite of AND gate&lt;/strong&gt; which means output is one when any of input is 1 whereas if both inputs is 1 output is 0&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;OR gate:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;If any of the input is high, it produces a high output.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Boolean algebra for OR gate is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;X = A + B&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_13.6.20_Pallavi_D22.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 227px; height: 277px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;NOT gate:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;It inverts the input. Whatever the input is given, it changes its value at the output.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Boolean algebra for NOT gate is X = X̅&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_13.6.20_Pallavi_D23.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 205px; height: 202px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From the above table, it is clear that the given &lt;strong&gt;truth table is for NOT gate&lt;/strong&gt;. Therefore option 3 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Stress:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;When a&amp;nbsp;force is applied on a body, there will be&amp;nbsp;relative displacement of the particles&amp;nbsp;and due to&amp;nbsp;property of elasticity, &lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;an&amp;nbsp;internal restoring force&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is developed which&amp;nbsp;tends to restore the body to its original state.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;internal restoring force acting per unit area of cross-section&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the deformed body is called&amp;nbsp;stress.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Stress = \frac{{Force{\rm{\;}}\left( F \right)}}{{Area{\rm{\;}}\left( A \right)}} = N{m^{ - 2}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Young&amp;rsquo;s modulus:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Young&amp;#39;s modulus a&amp;nbsp;modulus of elasticity, applicable to the stretching of wire, etc., equal to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;ratio of the applied load per unit area of the cross-section&lt;/strong&gt; to the increase in length per unit length.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;It is denoted as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;E or Y&lt;/strong&gt;. The unit of&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Young&amp;rsquo;s modulus is N m&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Y = \frac{{Stress}}{{Strain}} = \frac{{\left( {\frac{F}{A}} \right)}}{{\left( {\frac{{{\rm{\Delta }}l}}{l}} \right)}} = \frac{{Fl}}{{A{\rm{\;\Delta }}l}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Strain:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;It is defined as the&amp;nbsp;ratio of change in length to the original length. i.e.,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;It has no unit.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Strain = \frac{{Change{\rm{\;}}in{\rm{\;}}lenght{\rm{\;}}\left( {{\rm{\Delta }}l} \right)}}{{Original{\rm{\;}}lenght{\rm{\;}}\left( l \right)}} = \frac{{[{M^0}L{T^0}]}}{{\left[ {{M^0}L{T^0}} \right]}} = 1\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Pressure: &lt;/strong&gt;It is the component of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;force normal&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;to the area under consideration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Pressure = \frac{F}{A}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Its dimensions are&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;[ML&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;ndash;1&lt;/sup&gt;T&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;ndash;2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The pressure is a&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;scalar&amp;nbsp;quantity&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;since force is vector quantity&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;The SI unit of pressure is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Nm&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;ndash;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. It has been named as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;pascal&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;(Pa)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In the above explanation of all the options &amp;ndash;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Stress &amp;ndash; N/m&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;ndash; Force/area&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Young&amp;rsquo;s Modulus &amp;ndash; N/m&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;ndash; Force/area&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Strain &amp;ndash; No unit&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Pressure &amp;ndash; N/m&lt;sup style=&quot;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;ndash; Force/area&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;, the correct option is Strain.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Specific&amp;nbsp;heat:&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Specific&amp;nbsp;heat or&amp;nbsp;specific&amp;nbsp;heat&amp;nbsp;capacity&amp;nbsp;of a body is the&amp;nbsp;amount of&amp;nbsp;heat&amp;nbsp;required for a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;unit mass of the body&amp;nbsp;to raise the&amp;nbsp;temperature by 1 degree&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Celsius.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: circle;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is denoted by&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;C&amp;rdquo;&lt;/span&gt; or &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;ldquo;S&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;different&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;for&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;each substance&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its unit is &lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;al/g-&amp;deg;C&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CGS&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;joule/g-K&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;SI unit&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1 calorie = 4.186 Joule.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;It is given by,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(S=\frac{Q}{m \Delta t}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;​S&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;= specific heat of a substance, Q= Heat supplied to the object, m= mass of the substance, &amp;Delta; t = change in temperature.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q = 26400 J, m = 2 kg&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;T1 = 20&amp;deg;C = 20 + 273&amp;nbsp; = 293 K&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;T2 =&amp;nbsp;35&amp;deg;C = 35 + 273 = 308 K&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;Delta;T =&amp;nbsp; 35 - 20 = 15 K&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;we know that, specific heat is given by&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q = mC&amp;Delta;t&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 26400 = 2&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; C&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 15&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; C = 880 J/kg-K&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the specific&amp;nbsp;heat of aluminium will be 880 J/kg-K.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Projectile motion:&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;A&amp;nbsp;kind of&amp;nbsp;motion that is&amp;nbsp;experienced by an object when it&amp;nbsp;is projected near the Earth&amp;#39;s surface and it moves along a curved path under the action of gravitational force.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;maximum height a projectile&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;can attain:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{u_y^2}}{{2g}} = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity that makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a particle&amp;nbsp;moves in projectile motion, its&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;velocity has two components.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​​vertical component (u sin&amp;theta;) = u&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;horizontal component (u cos&amp;theta;) = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F2_J.K_Madhu_04.05.20__D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 413px; height: 238px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let the maximum height attained by the projectile is H,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At the maximum height, the ball will have zero velocity in vertical&amp;nbsp;direction i.e. v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt; = 0;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The ball can not go above this point because vertical velocity is zero at this point.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;By the third equation of motion in the y-direction&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 2 g H&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;0 = (u sin&amp;theta;)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 2 g H&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;time of flight of projectile&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is given by:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(T = \frac{2usinθ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity, makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;range of flight&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R = \frac{u^2sin2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity,&amp;nbsp;makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Electric Field:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Electric Force per unit positive charge at a given point gives field at that point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Electric Potential:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;The amount of work done required to be done per unit charge to bring a positive charge from infinity to that point&amp;nbsp;is called Electric Potential.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;relationship between Field and Potential:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;The relationship between&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;field and potential&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is given as&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{dV}{dr} = -E\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;dV = - E.dr&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For average estimation we can say that&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(E = \frac{Δ V}{Δ r}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;Delta;V is potential difference,&amp;nbsp;&amp;Delta;r is distance.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The field is &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;directed toward decreasing Potential.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;u&gt;Calculation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, here we have&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;Delta;V =&amp;nbsp;10&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;V&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;Delta;r = 1 cm = 10 &lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt; m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Field&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(E = \frac{Δ V}{Δ r}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\implies E = \frac{10^3}{10^{-2}} V/m = 10^{(3 +2)} V/m\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; E = 10 &lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt; V / m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So, the correct option is&amp;nbsp;10&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;5&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;V / m&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is option 3) i.e.&amp;nbsp;6.5 J&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Collisions in one dimension:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;​Let m&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and m&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;be the masses of two objects that undergo&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;inelastic collision&lt;/span&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From the principle of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;momentum conservation&lt;/span&gt;,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;m&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1i&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ m&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2i&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= (m&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ m&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;)v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;f&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;where v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1i&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the initial velocity of the moving object and v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;f&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the final combined velocity after collision.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(⇒ v_f = \frac{m_1v_{1i} +m_2v_{2i}}{m_1 +m_2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The loss in kinetic energy on collision is,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(⇒ ΔKE = \frac{1}{2}m_1v_{1i}^2 -\frac{1}{2}(m_1+m_2)v_f^2\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;CALCULATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;m&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 10 kg, m&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 5 kg&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;u&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 2 m/s, u&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0 m/s&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Using,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( v_f = \frac{m_1u_1+m_2u_2}{m_1 +m_2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( ⇒ v_f = \frac{10(2) + 5(0)}{10+5}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; v&lt;sub&gt;f&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.34 m/s&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Loss in kinetic energy,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( ΔKE = \frac{1}{2}m_1u_1^2 -\frac{1}{2}(m_1+m_2)v_f^2\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( ⇒ ΔKE = \frac{1}{2}\times 10 \times 2^2 -\frac{1}{2}\times (10+5)\times1.34^2\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&amp;Delta;KE = 6.5&amp;nbsp;J&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frequency of sound in open pipe =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{v}{2l}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Frequency of sound in close pipe =&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{v}{4l}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the frequency of open pipe is A and close pipe is B.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In that case,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A : B =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{v}{2l}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{v}{4l}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 2 : 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT :&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Power is&lt;/strong&gt; the &lt;strong&gt;rate of doing work&lt;/strong&gt; in an electrical circuit, the various equation for power calculation is given by&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(⇒ P = VI=I^2R=\frac{V^2}{R}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where V = Potential difference , R = Resistance, I= Current&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CALCULATION :&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given - P = 20 W,&amp;nbsp; I = 4Amp, V = 220 V, R = ?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The resistance of the motor can be written as&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(⇒ R = \frac{P}{I^{2}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(⇒ R = \frac{20}{4^{2}} = 1.25 \Omega\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The applied EMF can be calculated as&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; V = E - I R&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; E = V + IR = 220 +&amp;nbsp;4&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 1.25 = 225V&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;option 2 is the answer&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Dimensional formula:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;It&amp;nbsp;is a compound expression showing how and which of the fundamental quantities are involved in making that physical quantity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;dimension&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;principle of homogeneity &lt;/strong&gt;says that an equation is dimensionally correct only&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;if each term has the same dimension on both sides of the equation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CALCULATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given equation is x = at + bt&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The dimension of [x] will be equal to the dimension of [at] and [bt&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;[x] = [at]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;[a] = [x/t]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;katex&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px;  background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal;  line-height: inherit; text-rendering: auto; position: relative; letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;katex-html&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;base&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: relative; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; width: min-content;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mord mathnormal&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;has dimension of length and&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;katex&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px;  background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal;  line-height: inherit; text-rendering: auto; position: relative; letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;katex-html&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;base&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: relative; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; width: min-content;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mord mathnormal&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;has dimension of time so unit of&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;katex&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px;  background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal;  line-height: inherit; text-rendering: auto; position: relative; letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;katex-html&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;base&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: relative; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; width: min-content;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mord mathnormal&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;will be ms&lt;sup&gt;-1&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;[x] = [bt&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;[b] = [x/t&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;katex&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; line-height: inherit; text-rendering: auto; position: relative; letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;katex-html&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;base&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: relative; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; width: min-content;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mord mathnormal&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;has dimension of length and&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;katex&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; line-height: inherit; text-rendering: auto; position: relative; letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;katex-html&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;base&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: relative; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; width: min-content;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mord mathnormal&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: 0px 0px; position: static;&quot;&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;has dimension of time so unit of &lt;span style=&quot;white-space: nowrap;&quot;&gt;b&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;will be &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ms&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;-2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So the correct answer is &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: -0.36px;&quot;&gt;option 4.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the kinetic theory of gases, the average kinetic energy of a collection of gas molecules is directly proportional to absolute temperature only. i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;K.E=3/2&amp;times;k&amp;times;T, hence&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;K.E &amp;prop; T&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;where k = Boltzmann&amp;rsquo;s constant and T is the temperature in Kelvin.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the kinetic theory of gases, the molecules undergo&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;elastic collision&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;with the walls of the container and with each other.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;At absolute zero temperature&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e. at T = 0 K, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;average kinetic energy of gases reduces to zero&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;hence there is no collision within the gases.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kinetic theory of gases relates the macroscopic property of the gas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Macroscopic properties&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that can be visualized or measured by the naked eye; examples include pressure, temperature, and volume.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Correct option-&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Concept:-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;INSTANTANEOUS SPEED&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The speed of a moving object at a particular instant of time is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;instantaneous speed&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We can define velocity at a particular instant as the limiting value of average velocity when time interval ∆t approaches zero.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mathematically we can write the same as follows:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(v=\underset{\Delta t\to 0}{\mathop{\lim }}\,\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{dx}{dt}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When we calculate average velocity or speed, the selected time interval can be large or small.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;But when the time interval selected is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;infinitesimally small&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;then&amp;nbsp;it is known as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;instantaneous velocity&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;or&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;speed.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For a moving object, the instantaneous speed at any point is equal to the magnitude of instantaneous velocity but the average speed in a given time interval is always greater or equal to the magnitude of average velocity in that interval.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Calculation:-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given-&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Expression for distance in an upward direction, i.e. altitude&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(y=16{{t}^{2}}+4t+5\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Instantaneous speed&amp;nbsp;is given as-&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(v=\frac{dy}{dt}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\Rightarrow\frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{d\left( 16{{t}^{2}}+4t+5 \right)}{dt}=32t+4\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\therefore v=32t+4\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Initial speed means speed at t = 0 sec.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So at t = 0 sec, we have&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(v=32\times 0+4=4m/s\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\therefore v=4m/s\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, Option-&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is correct.&lt;/p&gt;

